arch:property.oc:show_val: F1 is a piece of worked antler. F2 and F3 are bone ring fragments. F4 is a point. This unit is a sort of doughnut dug around the inside of space 86, B.3, to expose the bases of the walls. It includes material from at least three separate depositional contexts, although most of the bone probably comes from a midden along the west wall. And it includes only parts of these contexts, an arbitrary slice to get at the walls. This is too bad, because what is here actually shows considerable integrity. No doubt this would be even more so if the depositional units were separate and complete. In general, this looks like a classic midden. There is a lot of material, fragmentation is not too great, there is a mix of many taxa. These include sheep/goat, cattle, equid, pig, a small carnivore, and most notably red deer. What is notable about the red deer is that it is not limited to heads and feet, but spread throughout the body, with an MNi of two. Some pieces are articulated. We have been picking up bits of this in some other sub-floor units. It is possible that this is not part of the midden per se, but a spread of feasting remains that preceded the beginning of construction. I would not be surprised if there is more red deer in this unit, or certainly this group of units, than the rest of the site combined, not counting antler. Sheep-size animals predominate, but by a lesser margin than usual. Large mammal bone is almost as common by volume. There are a couple of fragments of almost impossibly thick long bone cortex. I suppose they must be from a particularly robust aurochs bull, but they look like elephant. There are several bones from a perinatal sheep/goat. All body parts are represented for both sheep-size and large mammals. Ribs and vertebrae are perhaps a bit under-represented, but less so than usual. Meaty long bones seem unusually common; this looks like mainly post-consumption discard. Undigested phalanges are relatively few. There is quite a bit of digestion among the smaller fragments, so dog feces formed part of these deposits. Many of them still have what looks like traces of coprolite coating them, indicating a concentrated deposit of dog shit. There is little burning, most of it low temperature. Several instances of unfused epiphyses still in articulation shows that disturbance was minimal in at least some areas. In general the bone looks moderately processed: broken for marrow, perhaps broken a bit further in processing or through later processes, but not a lot of bone grease processing. The red deer remains are treated about the same as the rest. The only basis for suggesting a feast is the concentration of these unusual bones, and the hint that they may have lain across the top of the deposit(s). Some of them seem more weathered than most of the bone, supporting the notion that they lay exposed on top for a while. The dry sieved material also includes one fish bone and some bird, but bird seems under-represented for this volume. Four additional tools were found with the fauna: two point fragments, a ring fragment, and what seems to be ring-making waste. Sample 2 >4mm flotation 100% sorted, recorded as diagnostics and flot frags. A large sample that generally looks similar to the dry sieved, with a variety of taxa and body parts. Generally quite good surface condition, but a lot of digestion. There is some fish and one fragment of microfauna, no bird. Last number = 1169
Nerissa Russell, Lisa Yeomans, Louise Martin
